WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.840
My name is James Black, I'm the insights engineering lead in late stage at Roche, and today I'm

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:10.100
wearing my hat as the scientific computing environment product owner.

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:15.700
I'm talking about a project with Vegeta, who's one of our API engineers who helped us navigate

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:20.520
all of the data that's within our logs, and then also Christian who took a very badly

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:27.200
written POC by me and turned it into a data product.

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:32.320
So in this talk I'm going to cover two problems that we ran into.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:38.439
So one of them was we were building our scientific computing environment and we spent a lot of

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:41.400
time kind of understanding what the users needed.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:47.320
So we built this platform which hopefully was able to meet all the use cases which statisticians

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.799
and our statistical programmers and our real data scientists had.

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:56.599
But now we got to 1.0 and suddenly we were generating lots and lots of data on how they

00:00:56.599 --> 00:00:59.520
actually use the platform.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:04.839
So we started to ask, well can we start now incorporating what the users actually do into

00:01:04.839 --> 00:01:08.320
our decision making?

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:12.680
And the second problem was around optimizing use.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:18.440
So with our users, kind of historically, compute and particularly CPU compute is seen as a

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:21.320
free resource.

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:26.279
So we have over 1,200 users on this platform and when you're talking about that kind of

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:30.199
scale, one thing we know is that it is definitely not free.

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:34.559
So what could we do to kind of feed back to users to try and improve their use or at least

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:40.919
allow them to make educated decisions rather than having to limit stuff?

00:01:40.919 --> 00:01:45.800
So there's so much you can do with the operational data that a compute platform generates, but

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:48.360
I'm going to focus on four questions.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:53.320
So one of them was like what versions of R are people actually using at any one point

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:55.800
in time?

00:01:55.800 --> 00:02:00.080
And we had this question around what's the optimal way to handle interactive containers

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:03.239
because they spend a lot of time just sitting there.

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:07.599
So what should we do in terms of provisioning those kind of interactive environments for

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:08.600
people?

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:12.039
So this is one that's slightly hidden in the Connect documentation, but how can we make

00:02:12.039 --> 00:02:17.639
sure that the disk space on Connect is full of things people are actually using and not

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:21.440
a lot of failed apps or apps which are kind of five years old and people have forgotten

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:25.919
about or there's a cron job running every day for a project which hasn't been working

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:29.460
for like for many years.

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.240
And the last one was just even understanding who's using the platform.

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:38.199
So once we have this data in place, it's very easy for us to get really deep into what departments

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:42.639
are using it, what are the patterns of use, what components are used by different people

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:45.160
and things like that.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:50.240
So to kind of give some background on the compute environment I'm talking about, we

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:54.399
have one scientific computing environment and here I'm including kind of the tools that

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:56.119
sit around it.

00:02:56.119 --> 00:03:02.399
So we have data scientists, so from the real-world evidence team and right through to imaging

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:03.399
scientists.

00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:09.119
They're using the same kind of backend as our clinical trial, the people doing the clinical

00:03:09.119 --> 00:03:10.119
trial analysis.

00:03:10.119 --> 00:03:12.300
It's just the UIs are different.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:18.199
One of them is much more efficiency focused and for the data scientists the focus is agility.

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:24.639
But the pieces they share are things like the studies being in Git repos on GitLab.

00:03:24.639 --> 00:03:29.960
We have Posit Package Manager which is surfacing, currently it's surfacing all the R packages.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.360
Python is a little bit different, we use a mixture of Lmod and a couple of things in

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:35.679
Posit Package Manager.

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:39.800
A lot of our apps and for some departments the Kinect server is actually their results

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:40.800
portal.

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:44.600
So for instance in real-world evidence they treat it as a results portal for static content

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:45.960
as well.

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:52.039
We have a Kubernetes server with all those containers running those interactive jobs.

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:56.800
We have a HomePod, so this is like their home drive where people are storing things.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:59.880
We deal with patient data, so sometimes there's a risk they're storing things in their home

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:02.160
drive they shouldn't be storing there.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:03.559
And then we use Batch.

00:04:03.559 --> 00:04:09.279
So we have a proper HPC but we kind of treat Batch as a simplified HPC for those kind of

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:10.600
middle-of-the-road jobs.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:15.600
Like if it takes between an hour and six hours, AWS Batch is probably going to be a much easier

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:18.519
interface to work with.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:22.480
So under the hood these are all generating data.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:26.399
So for instance in the containers we have a Dockerfile, so we know exactly what version

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:29.920
of everything people are actively using at any one time.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:35.880
We know things like CPU use, I've kept the HPC out of scope here so we don't have GPUs,

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:40.119
but we also know things like when are they creating containers, when are they deleting

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:44.119
containers or are we the ones deleting it with our rules.

00:04:44.119 --> 00:04:49.000
In the HomePod we know how much space they're using up and we also are looking into things

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.600
like looking at data transfer within AWS.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:56.839
We obviously have all of the kind of HR information on people.

00:04:56.839 --> 00:04:58.600
Package Manager is a slightly weird one.

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:06.239
So CRAN downloads like statistics are available, but just like the CRAN downloads they're not

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:07.239
that useful.

00:05:07.239 --> 00:05:08.959
But we also have the Git repos.

00:05:08.959 --> 00:05:13.279
So we can actually go into things like the RNF lock file for a study and properly understand

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:16.200
which version of every package is being used.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:21.359
And something which GSK told me about just a couple days ago was also the API for flagging

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:25.519
what language is being used and things like that.

00:05:25.519 --> 00:05:30.519
And then finally for a connect we have information for every single object on stuff like when

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:35.559
it was last accessed, how many times it was accessed, did it actually successfully deploy

00:05:35.559 --> 00:05:39.040
and stuff like that.

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:42.619
So we do have a dashboard, but because I don't have that much time I'm just going to focus

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:44.059
on those four topics.

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:47.179
But we have this kind of living live dashboard.

00:05:47.179 --> 00:05:50.380
So if people are asking questions or we want to know something we can kind of dive into

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:53.299
it very easily.

00:05:53.299 --> 00:05:57.820
So going into the split of active containers over our versions.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:01.779
So when I was making these slides I looked in the dashboard to see what the current status

00:06:01.779 --> 00:06:07.019
was and you'd kind of think well there would be use cases where people are using an old

00:06:07.019 --> 00:06:08.019
container.

00:06:08.019 --> 00:06:11.220
Let's say they're still working on a study and a study might last a year.

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:13.859
So there could be quite a split there.

00:06:13.859 --> 00:06:17.859
Looking just at the containers with R, we actually have a lot of diversity in what people

00:06:17.859 --> 00:06:18.859
are using.

00:06:18.859 --> 00:06:20.739
And some of this is actually quite impressive.

00:06:20.739 --> 00:06:26.899
Like this person's still using R 4.00, they've been going in at least once every now and

00:06:26.899 --> 00:06:30.540
again to stop it auto deleting for many years.

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:33.980
That's like it's maybe four years they've been managing to do that.

00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:37.459
So they obviously haven't had a sabbatical or anything like that.

00:06:37.459 --> 00:06:41.660
But it really helps us understand like what versions of R are being used and we could

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:46.059
do the same for Python and we just have some less users there.

00:06:46.059 --> 00:06:47.600
But we can also start going deeper.

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:50.339
So we know things like the life of the container.

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:51.839
We know when it was created.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:52.980
We know who deleted it.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:55.459
Like was it us or was it the user?

00:06:55.459 --> 00:06:57.380
And we can start to look at different patterns.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:02.019
And I guess if you look at this plot, you can at least see the patterns for when things

00:07:02.019 --> 00:07:03.019
are also deleted.

00:07:03.019 --> 00:07:06.660
If they create a container, maybe visit it once and never come back because you can see

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:13.899
those lines appearing in the data when it comes to the life cycle of these containers.

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:18.339
So one of the other things that we can look into is this question around how often do

00:07:18.339 --> 00:07:21.420
the interactive containers sit idle.

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:29.859
So maybe to give a bit of background, we have our containers here in the Kubernetes server.

00:07:29.859 --> 00:07:33.940
But really behind the scenes, we have a whole bunch of worker nodes.

00:07:34.299 --> 00:07:37.820
In our current configuration, there's 64 CPUs per worker nodes.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:42.700
So it's basically this hugely horizontal scaling thing where every time it's adding a machine

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:47.899
of 64 CPUs as new containers are created.

00:07:47.899 --> 00:07:52.299
So if we said, okay, we want this to kind of at least mirror a laptop.

00:07:52.299 --> 00:07:56.179
So we give each user 16 reserved CPUs.

00:07:56.179 --> 00:08:00.420
That means we're only putting a few containers onto every server and our costs are relatively

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:01.420
high.

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:05.380
So you can kind of suspect that most people, you know, they're not working 24 hours a day

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:07.859
running things across 16 cores.

00:08:07.859 --> 00:08:14.380
So how can we optimize this to understand what's the best way to run this Kubernetes

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:15.739
server?

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:20.459
And so because we have the data, we actually have like a living track record of what people

00:08:20.459 --> 00:08:21.459
are actually doing.

00:08:21.459 --> 00:08:25.779
And so looking at our statisticians and our statistical programmers, we can see in this

00:08:25.779 --> 00:08:30.779
plot that pretty much everyone has a container doing nothing most of the time.

00:08:30.779 --> 00:08:33.340
So zero is the one where almost everyone is.

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:37.219
There's a couple of people who managed to request all 16 containers.

00:08:37.219 --> 00:08:40.739
I think it's only a couple, it's literally a couple of people in our department, but

00:08:40.739 --> 00:08:42.700
actually they're not using the full 16.

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:47.700
So 16 probably wasn't a good default for us to have in the first place.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:54.460
And we can definitely conclude that reserving 16 cores per container is probably a bad idea

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:57.179
and it's definitely a waste of money.

00:08:57.179 --> 00:09:01.580
So we can try and figure out like what actually is the best balance to optimize the number

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:04.460
of containers we can throw onto each worker node.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:07.419
And we can really drive down the price then.

00:09:07.419 --> 00:09:10.659
And I think one of the cool things we can do is even dig a bit deeper.

00:09:10.659 --> 00:09:16.179
So for instance, our real world data scientists and statistical programmers, we have different

00:09:16.179 --> 00:09:18.179
levels of over provisioning.

00:09:18.179 --> 00:09:22.599
So we have different kind of numbers of containers per worker node, depending on what role the

00:09:22.599 --> 00:09:27.799
person does within the company.

00:09:27.799 --> 00:09:32.479
So this is one, as I mentioned, it's actually in the docs for Connect, but like really hidden

00:09:32.479 --> 00:09:33.479
in there.

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:36.239
There's actually R code as well to do this.

00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:39.919
But one of the things we can look into is making sure the disk space on our Connect

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:47.080
server is, I mean, not full of stuff that doesn't work or is very old.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.799
So we decided to kind of look into this.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:54.679
And when we ran the scripts that Posit has in their documentation, we saw that there

00:09:54.679 --> 00:10:01.599
actually were 707 items where they click the publish button, it's stale, like it was never

00:10:01.599 --> 00:10:05.640
successfully deployed and the user didn't come back and get it working.

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:09.080
So this was 707 items that were published.

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:12.260
The person may have tried to publish them again, maybe they didn't, but they basically

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:14.239
never successfully deployed.

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:18.479
So it's essentially, you know, if it's a 50 megabyte app, it's just 50 megabytes of data

00:10:18.479 --> 00:10:23.039
sitting there that does absolutely nothing and never has.

00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:25.719
And I think there's a little quirk in there, because if you're just pressing the button

00:10:25.719 --> 00:10:29.440
in RStudio and it fails the first time, you keep making new ones.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:34.320
So sometimes this was like they made actually 12, it took them 12 attempts to publish, which

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:40.400
then means we have 11 dead ones that are just sitting on the server as duplicated objects.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:45.239
And then we also looked at like how long it had been since people had touched an object.

00:10:45.239 --> 00:10:50.000
So this was across everything, like across APIs, static, shiny apps, like when was the

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:51.919
last time it was touched?

00:10:51.919 --> 00:10:56.119
And so we had 502 items that hadn't been viewed in the last year.

00:10:56.119 --> 00:10:58.900
We also have retention policies within the company.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:01.780
So this is something where, you know, there could be some hard deadlines where if it hasn't

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:05.919
been modified in three years, we may want to automatically delete it or at least tell

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:11.059
the user this is about to get deleted because of our retention policies.

00:11:11.059 --> 00:11:16.059
So one thing we could do, and actually, again, the code for this is already in the Connect

00:11:16.059 --> 00:11:23.900
documentation, but we can go in and automatically start deleting using a cron job those items

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:26.020
which actually were never successfully deployed.

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:30.739
So you can imagine if you try to deploy it, you fail, you don't come back within 30 days.

00:11:30.739 --> 00:11:33.900
We can assume we can safely delete that.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:37.580
And then I think for the 502 is something we're still trying to figure out the best

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:38.580
strategy.

00:11:38.580 --> 00:11:42.500
So retention policies, at least there's a floor where it will get deleted, but then

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:47.780
we can at least start to inform users that, hey, you've got this content that's running

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:51.940
and also reminding people about their cron jobs because I think there's a lot of jobs

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:57.619
where people have set something on a schedule within Connect and then forget about it.

00:11:57.619 --> 00:12:04.919
So the last example I had was kind of understanding what teams are actually using our platform.

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:09.359
So our platform was built for specific departments, but we have a whole bunch of people that have

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:12.679
come in from other departments to use it as well.

00:12:12.679 --> 00:12:18.239
And we could really get into the details on how people are using the platform and which

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:21.239
parts of the platform as well.

00:12:21.239 --> 00:12:24.559
So I mentioned there's a lot you could do with that information, but this is just looking

00:12:24.559 --> 00:12:26.119
at one component.

00:12:26.119 --> 00:12:31.719
So within the frequency of interactive containers, we can really dig into how often are people

00:12:31.719 --> 00:12:34.599
actually going into an interactive container?

00:12:34.599 --> 00:12:36.400
And this is where they actually are doing something.

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:41.719
So we're taking into account CPU use and if the container was idle or they were actively

00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:46.479
in it on that particular day, and we kind of get this picture around like what is the

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:51.880
use daily, weekly, monthly, or even less than that across, I handpicked these departments

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:57.820
because they were interesting numbers, but they're across different departments.

00:12:57.820 --> 00:13:00.900
And there's a lot of different ways you could tackle this.

00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:04.419
And because we have our HR information, we could also split this like are they an individual

00:13:04.419 --> 00:13:08.260
contributor or are they a manager and things like that.

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:12.419
I mean, it's also really useful when you have teams who are coming in and using your platform

00:13:12.419 --> 00:13:17.400
who aren't the original stakeholders, it can be quite useful to understand where else it's

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:20.400
being used.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:25.780
So one thing we started relatively recently is also seeing if we could try to kind of

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:29.919
positively influence use in our users.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:33.520
So one thing we want to kind of avoid is like forcing them to make a ticket if they want

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:38.859
like more than one virtual CPU, but so how could we do things to try and encourage kind

00:13:38.859 --> 00:13:44.799
of respectful use of the resources without having to put in limits or making them fill

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:47.840
in the ticket or something like that?

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:54.020
So I looked in the data when I made these slides and took one statistician who I know

00:13:54.020 --> 00:13:55.179
does simulations.

00:13:55.179 --> 00:13:57.820
So that was his real number.

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:02.659
He had 2,971 CPU hours in July.

00:14:02.659 --> 00:14:08.219
So for this particular user, I'm not using the real math is a lot more complicated because

00:14:08.219 --> 00:14:14.159
of firstly the corporate rates and then also like how the system is actually set up.

00:14:14.159 --> 00:14:18.640
But using kind of a simplistic formula, that's about 62 US dollars.

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:23.859
So we can actually feed back to users like, hey, that job you ran, each time you're running

00:14:23.859 --> 00:14:26.099
it, that's $6 or something like that.

00:14:26.099 --> 00:14:28.719
If you ran it 10 times.

00:14:28.719 --> 00:14:33.200
When I submitted the abstract, we had just started looking at the carbon footprint.

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:37.960
I think in terms of like this being something we want to positively influence the users,

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:41.799
the carbon footprint is interesting if we look at it at the platform level.

00:14:41.799 --> 00:14:45.400
And it's definitely a useful thing to communicate back.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:50.000
If we're talking about the HPCs where you've got like much more CPU use and GPU use and

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:51.500
stuff like that.

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:57.200
One of the things we found though is that using the kind of available code to calculate

00:14:57.200 --> 00:15:01.479
that, it's actually relatively low if we're talking about a statistical programmer.

00:15:01.479 --> 00:15:07.719
So this person who had the almost 3,000 hours in a month, it was actually only about 0.13

00:15:07.719 --> 00:15:10.039
kilograms of CO2.

00:15:10.039 --> 00:15:14.559
And we kind of need to make sure when we're communicating stuff back to users, it's steering

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:16.719
people in the direction we want them to go.

00:15:16.719 --> 00:15:20.320
Because Roche also does stuff like when you book a flight through the company, they tell

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:22.059
you your carbon footprint.

00:15:22.059 --> 00:15:24.500
And when I was making the slides, I got back the flights.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:27.219
So the flight here was 9,000 kilograms.

00:15:27.219 --> 00:15:32.739
This person who did a crazy amount of simulations was 0.13 kilograms.

00:15:32.739 --> 00:15:36.419
And is that actually going to steer the person in the right direction if we start sharing

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:38.340
this information back to them?

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:39.979
Maybe they'll say, actually, that's hardly anything.

00:15:39.979 --> 00:15:44.419
I can now run like, you know, I can increase my bootstrap to 100,000 or something like

00:15:44.419 --> 00:15:46.059
that.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:48.000
Yeah.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.679
And so this is just a mockup because we haven't started doing it yet.

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:55.880
But one thing we've talked about is maybe we could put some rules in where we think

00:15:55.880 --> 00:15:59.080
there's something happening, which is a behavior which we want to modify.

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:03.919
Could we actually start feeding them back automatically by making some rules?

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:04.919
So this is an example.

00:16:04.919 --> 00:16:08.000
We have a lot of people who make a lot of containers and they just don't log into them

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.000
again.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.479
So they might make like 11 containers over the span of a month.

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:16.320
And each one they kind of work in for a day and just don't come back.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:18.619
And sometimes, you know, it's the exact same image.

00:16:18.619 --> 00:16:21.820
So they're just making a new container each time they start working.

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:25.619
So we can start doing stuff like identifying those users and maybe feeding back to them

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:29.219
like, hey, you know, because we wait a little while to close these, that's actually quite

00:16:29.219 --> 00:16:31.059
expensive what you're doing.

00:16:31.059 --> 00:16:35.739
Can we please encourage you to kind of stick to one image and one container?

00:16:35.739 --> 00:16:39.260
And we can, that example from Connect, I think is almost like a no brainer.

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:43.919
We can start feeding back to people when there's content that's maybe forgotten.

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:48.119
And definitely when there's content that's not actually working.

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:52.119
Yeah, so where are we now?

00:16:52.119 --> 00:16:57.359
We have this dashboard which provides transparent metrics on data that was already there.

00:16:57.359 --> 00:16:59.919
Like we didn't make this data.

00:16:59.919 --> 00:17:03.799
All of our stuff from the Kubernetes cluster that was just sitting in Prometheus, and it

00:17:03.799 --> 00:17:07.400
was used by our informatics team to kind of monitor the platform.

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:11.699
But it was also available to us on the business side to kind of understand the users of the

00:17:11.699 --> 00:17:13.939
platform.

00:17:13.939 --> 00:17:17.780
And so now when we kind of get into these questions, like I can see Doug, who leads

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:22.979
our validation strategy here, when he starts asking me like how long do people use particular

00:17:22.979 --> 00:17:27.140
versions of R and things like that, we actually know that.

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:33.140
Like we know the splits across different versions of R for our users by department.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:35.900
Like we can really drill into the stuff like that.

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:41.319
Yeah, and soon we'll figure out exactly what we want to communicate back to users and how

00:17:41.319 --> 00:17:42.719
we want to influence them.

00:17:42.719 --> 00:17:46.560
But we could start to try and kind of lower costs or at least allow them to make more

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:52.359
informed decisions based on their usage of the platform.

00:17:52.359 --> 00:17:58.760
And I think one thing which I've added just before I gave this talk was from that conversation

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:03.880
with GSK just a few days ago where a lot of people are asking similar questions.

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:08.380
So maybe there's an opportunity to kind of share more of this code so that people could

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:12.119
just pick it up and, you know, automatically be able to build these kind of dashboards

00:18:12.119 --> 00:18:15.219
understanding their users.

00:18:15.219 --> 00:18:25.260
So yeah, thank you.

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:26.260
Thank you.

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:33.439
So have your efforts so far changed user perceptions of SCE as free?

00:18:33.439 --> 00:18:39.079
Yes, I think as I mentioned before, we want to kind of move away from relying on forcing

00:18:39.079 --> 00:18:42.239
people to fill in a ticket.

00:18:42.239 --> 00:18:44.000
That's what we currently do for GPUs.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.599
So if you want to use a GPU and you don't sit in the imaging team, you basically have

00:18:47.599 --> 00:18:50.760
to try and convince us that you should be allowed to use one.

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:55.119
So I think we definitely are getting across the message, but it's not the way we want

00:18:55.119 --> 00:18:56.119
to get the message across.

00:18:56.119 --> 00:18:57.780
Like, I don't want to have tickets for that.

00:18:57.780 --> 00:19:02.020
I want them to make a decision and make a good decision.

00:19:02.020 --> 00:19:05.500
Was there any data that was harder to obtain than you would have liked?

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:10.619
And what other tools did you need to use in order to get that data?

00:19:10.619 --> 00:19:15.300
I think the Prometheus logs themselves are not that easy to access.

00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:21.900
So there's some stuff where API engineers pushing it into an SQL database for us.

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:25.800
So yeah, there's definitely some things where maybe they're not collecting it yet.

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:30.959
So like AWS Batch, that wasn't actually available when we were first talking about it.

00:19:30.959 --> 00:19:34.800
And so they had to actually start keeping that information.

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:37.640
But it's all, I think it's relatively easy for them to keep.

00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:38.640
Sure.

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:40.680
Let's thank James again for a great talk.

00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:52.900
Thank you.

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:53.900
Thank you.

00:19:53.900 --> 00:19:54.900
Thank you.

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:54.900


